```suggestion
        double operator()(std::size_t i, std::size_t N) const
        { return hann(i, N, PERIODIC);};
```

How about this?   Like in general don't template on return type and just make everything return `double`.  Consider the hann code:
```
        const R phi = (2.0 * pi * i) / size;
        return 0.5 - 0.5 * std::cos(phi);
```
`(2.0 * pi * i) / size` is a `double`, which if `R` is `float` gets downcast to `float`, then the `float` version of `cos` runs on it and gives a less accurate result than it could have.  And then it gets converted back to `double` again by `0.5 *` before being cast back to `float` implicitly.   And `float` isn't faster than `double` on most CPUs.  So if this is all just `double` internally people will get more accurate results.  They can still stick it in a `matrix<float>` if they want certainly, but letting the cast to `float` only happen one at the very end will make the resulting value more accurate.  As well as simplifying the code here too.  Might even run faster since a bunch of float/double conversions would be removed.

