Not dumb! Good question. 

The other way around would work, but not that. The target type for the "atomic targets" (`python_source`, `go_package`, `python_requirement`, etc) is what we directly operate on and how we know what semantics to use: such as whether to try running tests on a Python file or not. Note that it's possible for example to have a `.py` file in a `file` target vs `python_source` vs `python_test` - the semantics all change based on which you choose.

It is totally plausible, though, to have one single generic target generator!

```python
gen_targets(
   name="generator",
   metadata={
       ["**/*.py"]: {"target_type": "python_source", "skip_pylint": True},
       ["**/*.java"]: {"target_type": "java_source"}
    }
)
```

Of course, that's not very intuitive not ergonomic, so I think it's better to have `python_sources`, `python_tests`, etc.

