I feel that for our most used commands, like az account, I have to be careful not to turn our auto-gen content into a tutorial.  :-)  Also, we have a Learn H2 planned so customers can drop down to working How-to guides and tutorials that are more complex in nature.  (Because of this I also feel that we should limit hard-coding HTTPS links in autogen as much as possible.)  Keeping all this in mind, I feel `--query` examples are appropriate for key commands.  There is a balance to be achieved that **leans toward no query examples.**  

@chasewilson, I don't want to replicate [How to query Azure CLI command output using a JMESPath query](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/query-azure-cli?view=azure-cli-latest&tabs=concepts%2Cbash) in autogen.  I do want to use `--query` judiciously to help our customers start thinking about using the Azure CLI in multi-step scripts and variables.

Let's revisit this discussion once we get `az accoun`t, `az group1, and `az someService` completed.  I think we'll start to see a good pattern of examples by then, and maybe need to backtrack on `--query` if we think we've taken it too far.  Sound good?

